18 "20-2-37.
19 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
20 (1) 'Federal agency' means the United States Department of Education or any other
21 agency, as such term is defined in 44 U.S.C. Section 3502.
22 (2) 'Guidance document' means any statement of general applicability issued by a federal
23 agency or by an official of such federal agency that sets forth a policy on a statutory,
24 regulatory, or technical issue or an interpretation of a statutory or regulatory issue;
25 provided, however, that such term shall not include a rule or other regulatory action that
26 has the force and effect of law promulgated in accordance with the notice and comment
27 rule-making requirements of the federal Administrative Procedure Act. Such term shall
28 include, but shall not be limited to, advisories, announcements, bulletins, circulars,
29 directives, letters, manuals, memoranda, notices, policy statements, and media, news, and
30 press releases. Such term shall encompass all guidance materials, regardless of format,
31 and shall include, but shall not be limited to, audio files and recordings; documents in
32 digital, electronic, or hard copy format; video files and recordings; internet posts; and
33 software applications. Such term shall be construed broadly to effectuate the purpose and
34 intent of this Code section.
35 (b) The State School Superintendent and the Department of Education shall take all steps
36 reasonably necessary to implement guidance documents from a federal agency, including,
37 but not limited to, directives related to expanding educational freedom and opportunities
38 for families.
39 (c)(1) Within 15 calendar days of receiving a guidance document from a federal agency
40 which the State School Superintendent or the State Board of Education deems relevant and
41 applicable to the duties, responsibilities, or business of the Department of Education, the
42 Department of Education shall publish such guidance document in accordance with the
43 requirements of subsection (d) of this Code section.
